  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concern—it's a lived reality for many who've spent decades in the field. As a data scientist who's seen the numbers and the human stories, I've witnessed how the fear of confirming negative stereotypes about one's group can undermine performance. For instance, when a young woman in my class at the university I attended—back when I was a student—was struggling with calculus because she felt she was 'not good enough' in a male-dominated classroom, it wasn't just about the math. It was about the weight of expectations she carried. The problem isn't that people aren't smart; it's that the environment can make them doubt themselves. I've worked with many people over the years who, despite having strong technical skills, were hesitant to speak up because they worried about being judged. We must address this head-on, not with token gestures but with real, systemic changes. For example, in my current role, I've implemented peer mentoring programs where students from underrepresented groups work alongside those who've succeeded. This helps build confidence and shows that success is possible. Another approach is to normalize diverse perspectives in the classroom, which reduces the pressure to conform to a single 'correct' way of thinking. The key is to create spaces where everyone feels safe to contribute without fear of judgment. It's not about changing the inherent abilities of individuals but about changing the environment to support them. After all, as a Christian, I believe in the dignity of every person, and that's why I think we should focus on fostering an inclusive culture where everyone can thrive.",
